{"atom_id": "ig34_p0301_a010", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 301, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.7.5 Ophthalmic Examinations (OE)", "atom_type": "HEADING", "verbatim": "OE – Assumptions", "heading_level": 5, "sibling_index": 3, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.3", "ts": "2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0301_a011", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 301, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.7.5 Ophthalmic Examinations (OE)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "In ophthalmic studies, the eyes are usually sites of treatment. It is appropriate to identify sites using the variable FOCID. When FOCID is used to identify the eyes, it is recommended that the values \"OD\" (oculus dexter, right eye), \"OS\" (oculus sinister, left eye), and \"OU\" (oculus uterque, both eyes) be used in FOCID. These terms are the exclusively preferred terms used by the ophthalmology community as abbreviations for the expanded Latin terms, and are included in the CDISC Ophthalmic Focus of Study Specific Interest (DEFOCUS) codelist.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.3", "ts": "2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0301_a012", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 301, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.7.5 Ophthalmic Examinations (OE)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "In any study that uses FOCID, FOCID would be included in records in any subject-level domain representing findings, interventions, or events (e.g., Adverse Events) related to the eyes. Whether or not FOCID is used in a study, --LOC and --LAT should be populated in records related to the eyes. The value in OELOC may be \"EYE\" but may also be part of the OE value (e.g., \"RETINA\", \"CORNEA\").", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.3", "ts": "2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0301_a013", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 301, "page_region": "middle", "parent_section": "§6.3.7.5 Ophthalmic Examinations (OE)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Any Identifiers, Timing variables, or Findings general observation class qualifiers may be added to the OE domain, but the following qualifiers would not generally be used: --MODIFY, --NOTES, --SUFFIX, --POS, --BODSYS, --ORREFL, --STREFC, --STREPN, --CHRON, --DISTR, --ANTREG, --LEAD, --FAST, --TOX, --TOXGR, --LLOQ, --ULOQ.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.3", "ts": "2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0301_a014", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 301, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.3.7.5 Ophthalmic Examinations (OE)", "atom_type": "HEADING", "verbatim": "OE – Examples", "heading_level": 5, "sibling_index": 4, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.3", "ts": "2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0301_a015", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 301, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.3.7.5 Ophthalmic Examinations (OE)", "atom_type": "HEADING", "verbatim": "Example 1", "heading_level": 6, "sibling_index": 1, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.3", "ts": "2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0301_a016", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 301, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.3.7.5 Ophthalmic Examinations (OE)", "atom_type": "SENTENCE", "verbatim": "This example shows a general anterior segment examination performed on each eye at 1 visit, with the purpose of evaluating general abnormalities.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.3", "ts": "2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0301_a017", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 301, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.3.7.5 Ophthalmic Examinations (OE)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Rows 1-2: Represent an overall interpretation (i.e., normal/abnormal) finding from the anterior segment examination. OEDTC=\"2012-01-19\", OELOC indicates that the assessor examined the lens and OELAT indicates which lens was examined.", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.3", "ts": "2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
{"atom_id": "ig34_p0301_a018", "source": "SDTMIG_v3.4", "page": 301, "page_region": "bottom", "parent_section": "§6.3.7.5 Ophthalmic Examinations (OE)", "atom_type": "LIST_ITEM", "verbatim": "Row 3: Represents an abnormality observed during the anterior segment examination of the right eye. OEDIR=\"MULTIPLE\" and indicates multiple directionality values are applicable. OELOC, OELAT, and the multiple OEDIR values specify the location of the abnormality represented in the observed abnormality (i.e., red visible) was determined to be clinically significant (OECLSIG=\"Y\").", "heading_level": null, "sibling_index": null, "figure_ref": null, "cross_refs": [], "extracted_by": {"subagent_type": "oh-my-claudecode:writer", "prompt_version": "P0_writer_pdf_v1.3", "ts": "2026-04-27T00:00:00Z"}}
